Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Dice @tomato{1} into ½-inch pieces. Quarter @lemon{1}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @Italian chicken sausage mix{9%oz}, scallion whites, and @Italian seasoning{1%tbsp}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until sausage is browned and scallions are softened, ~{3-5%minutes} (the sausage will finish cooking in step 4).

> Chicken Sausage is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.

Stir in tomato and cook until just softened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Turn off heat.

Once water is boiling, gently add @spinach and ricotta ravioli{9%oz} to pot. Reduce to a low simmer. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente and floating to the top, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water (1 cup for 4 servings), then drain.

> TIP: Gently shake strainer with ravioli in it to remove as much moisture as possible.

Stir @chicken stock concentrate{1}, a squeeze of lemon juice, and a small splash of reserved pasta cooking water into pan with sausage mixture. Cook over low heat, scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pan, until sausage is cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @sour cream{1/4%cup} and @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) until melted and combined. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: If needed, stir in more reserved cooking water a splash at a time until sauce reaches a creamy consistency.

Gently stir drained ravioli into pan with sauce. Season with salt and pepper. Add lemon juice to taste.

Divide pasta between plates or bowls. Garnish with scallion greens. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side.